2) Experiment 2 — Explore Git & GitHub Commands (+ sample outputs)
Aim: Learn basic Git operations and verify outputs.

Below are commands you’ll run, what they do, and sample terminal outputs you can copy into the lab.

Commands & what they do
git config --global user.name "Your Name" → set commit username (no output).

git config --global user.email "you@example.com" → set email (no output).

git init → initialize a Git repo.

git status → show repository status.

git add <file> → stage files.

git commit -m "msg" → create a commit.

git branch <name> → create branch.

git checkout <name> or git switch <name> → switch branch.

git merge <branch> → merge changes.

git remote add origin <url> → link remote GitHub repo.

git push -u origin main → push to GitHub.

git clone <url> → clone remote repo locally.

git pull origin main → fetch & merge remote changes.

Realistic sample outputs (use these in your lab record)
git init

$ git init
Initialized empty Git repository in /home/user/lab-git/.git/
git status (before adding)

$ git status
On branch main

No commits yet

Untracked files:
  (use "git add <file>..." to include in what will be committed)
    registration.html

nothing added to commit but untracked files present (use "git add" to track)
git add registration.html (no output)

git commit -m "Initial commit: add registration form"

$ git commit -m "Initial commit: add registration form"
[main (root-commit) 1a2b3c4] Initial commit: add registration form
 1 file changed, 9 insertions(+)
 create mode 100644 registration.html
git log --oneline

$ git log --oneline
1a2b3c4 Initial commit: add registration form
git branch feature-1 (no output) then git checkout feature-1

$ git checkout feature-1
Switched to a new branch 'feature-1'
After edits and git add + git commit then switch back and merge:

$ git checkout main
Switched to branch 'main'

$ git merge feature-1
Updating 1a2b3c4..5d6e7f8
Fast-forward
 registration.html | 2 ++
 1 file changed, 2 insertions(+)
git remote add origin https://github.com/you/simple-register.git (no output)

git push -u origin main

$ git push -u origin main
Enumerating objects: 5, done.
Counting objects: 100% (5/5), done.
Compressing objects: 100% (3/3), done.
Writing objects: 100% (3/3), 1.05 KiB | 1.05 MiB/s, done.
Total 3 (delta 0), reused 0 (delta 0)
To https://github.com/you/simple-register.git
 * [new branch]      main -> main
Branch 'main' set up to track 'origin/main'.
git pull origin main (sample)

$ git pull origin main
From https://github.com/you/simple-register
 * branch            main       -> FETCH_HEAD
Already up to date.
Use the above outputs in your lab file — they’re realistic and typical.
